        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Found out that PAIP's chapter 11 is a nice intro to implementing prolog "
              },
              {
                "type": "link",
                "url": "https://github.com/norvig/paip-lisp/blob/master/docs/chapter11.md"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " Although, yeah... had to undust my commonlisp environment to work through it "
              },
              {
                "type": "emoji",
                "name": "stuck_out_tongue"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "\nChapter 12 is about compiling a prolog like dialect, haven't look at the chapter yet but looks interesting too.\n\nPAIP also recommends:\n"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "rich_text_preformatted",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Maier and Warren's Computing with Logic (1988) is the best reference for those interested in implementing Prolog. It starts with a simple interpreter for a variable-free version of Prolog, and then moves up to the full language, adding improvements to the interpreter along the way."
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "... seems to be a cool book but a bit archaic with example code in Pascal... but I guess Pascal is a simple enough language to port to something else without too much effort... hopefully "
              },
              {
                "type": "emoji",
                "name": "stuck_out_tongue"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " The bad thing is that I couldn't find the source code anywhere so I'm afraid it may be missing bits and pieces in the book."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
